{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595634","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595634"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:07:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:07:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15373"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15373"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.02,0,0.24,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8064"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74904"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8064"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8397"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19579"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23443"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74904"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESmall bowel gangrene is a severe condition resulting from compromised blood supply to the bowel, leading to tissue necrosis. Histological examination of affected tissue can reveal specific pathological features.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features is most characteristic of small bowel gangrene on this histological examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transmural haemorrhage","Intact mucosal architecture","Increased goblet cell density","Submucosal fibrosis","Hyperplastic lymphoid follicles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most characteristic feature of small bowel gangrene on histological examination is \u003Cstrong\u003Etransmural haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs due to the loss of blood supply, leading to necrosis and bleeding throughout the entire thickness of the bowel wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntact mucosal architecture\u003C/strong\u003E - In gangrene, the mucosal architecture is typically disrupted due to necrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased goblet cell density\u003C/strong\u003E - Goblet cell density is not typically increased in gangrenous tissue\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubmucosal fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E - Fibrosis is not a feature of acute gangrene, which is characterised by necrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperplastic lymphoid follicles\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a feature of gangrene, which involves tissue necrosis and haemorrhage\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small bowel gangrene is characterised by transmural haemorrhage, necrosis, and loss of normal mucosal architecture.","Histological examination of gangrenous bowel tissue reveals extensive tissue damage and inflammatory cell infiltration.","Gangrene in the bowel can result from compromised blood supply, leading to tissue necrosis."],"references":["Oldenburg WA, Lau LL, Rodenberg TJ, Edmonds HJ, Burger CD. Acute mesenteric ischemia: a clinical review. Arch Intern Med. 2004 May 24;164(10):1054-62. doi: 10.1001/archinte.164.10.1054. PMID: 15159262.","Sise MJ. Acute mesenteric ischemia. Surg Clin North Am. 2014 Feb;94(1):165-81. doi: 10.1016/j.suc.2013.10.012. PMID: 24267504.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","\u0022Histopathology of small bowel gangrene from volvulus, showing transmural hemorrhage and dilated blood vessels.\u0022 by Mikael H\u00e4ggstr\u00f6m, M.D. is is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15373"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21158"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21158"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/o8O9T93nzHtwEOEfmJdQh14Uo1JeYu.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/o8O9T93nzHtwEOEfmJdQh14Uo1JeYu.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1160,"height":857}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60400"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T05:07:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T23:37:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8064"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74904"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a juni